This is related to a bug in Agave. When you query the system/roles/<username> endpoint it does not properly send a list of roles. For example:

```
$ curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $tok" $base/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs/roles/fooy

{
    "message": null,
    "result": {
        "_links": {
            "parent": {
                "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs"
            },
            "profile": {
                "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/profiles/v2/fooy"
            },
            "self": {
                "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs/roles/fooy"
            }
        },
        "role": "OWNER",
        "username": "fooy"
    },
    "status": "success",
    "version": "2.1.6-rbf84964"
}
```
Note that result is a dictionary. However, if you query the system roles endpoint instead you do get a list:

```
 $ curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $tok" $base/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs/roles
{
    "message": null,
    "result": [
        {
            "_links": {
                "parent": {
                    "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs"
                },
                "profile": {
                    "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/profiles/v2/fooy"
                },
                "self": {
                    "href": "https://public.tenants.prod.agaveapi.co/systems/v2/python-sdk-test-stor-jfs/roles/fooy"
                }
            },
            "role": "OWNER",
            "username": "fooy"
        }
    ],
    "status": "success",
    "version": "2.1.6-rbf84964"
}
```

I'll get a ticket raised in the Agave Jira system.

@stefanv : the code for using the high and low threshold callables was inspired by this (and my own uses in the past): https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canny_edge_detector#Robust_method_to_determine_the_dual-threshold_value

There, the lower threshold value is set to half of the higher value (ie requires calling the higher threshold callable). In general then, the low threshold callable gets fed the output of calling the high threshold callable, ie `low_threshold(magnitude [magnitude<high_threshold])`.

Otherwise, to obtain the same result, the high_threshold function would have to be passed in as part of the low_threshold callable.

