@dhermes I don't like implicit changing behavior. I.e.:

    datastore.put(e)  # to default project
    set_client(client)
    ... lots of non datastore code
    datastore.put(e)  # now to some other project

Us being able to do the smart thing for users that don't need or want extra configuration is fine.

@dhermes yes idiomatic is important. But are you saying that passing in the connection everywhere is more idiomatic in python? ISTM that if there isn't a clear more idiomatic way to do things, being consistent is a better policy.

@jgeewax fair point, maybe client is the better name (but then you could still have a Database/Dataset which contained a client that you could interact with directly).

If you want your callback to know about the policy it is "working for", I'd suggest something like:

```python
class Callback(object):

    def __init__(self):
        self.close_event = threading.Event()

    @property
    def done(self):
        return self.close_event.is_set()

    def __call__(self, message):
        if is_done(message):
            self.close_event.set()
        return handle_message(message)


def main():
    policy = subscriber.subscription(...)
    callback = Callback()
    future = policy.open(callback)

    while True:
        time.sleep(15)
        if callback.done:
            break

    policy.close()
```

----

> may I ask why the publisher returns the result when it sends a message

I assume you mean the following:

```python
future = publisher.publish(topic_path, b'some data', moo='lah')
message_id = future.result()
```

The "best" answer might be that those futures (i.e. the ones from `PublisherClient.publish()`) actually have something to return (we [do a "sanity check"][1] that each message in the publish corresponds to a future on the batch).

>  I didn't call any close method on that

By default, when you call `publisher.publish(...)` it actually pushes the message onto a `Batch` (rather than blocking the main thread). That batch has a short lifespan (0.05s by default) and once that lifespan is over, the batch will commit in a worker thread (that was spawned and sleeping since the batch was created).

> are the publish events seen as individual in this case and the whole thing is done in one go, whereas subscription is a continuous event stream?

A `publish()` is something "bounded", i.e. here is exactly one message, please publish it. Whereas a subscription is an open-ended stream of messages from a given topic, both the number of messages and the lifetime of the topic are unknown / unbounded.

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/blob/pubsub-0.29.4/pubsub/google/cloud/pubsub_v1/publisher/batch/thread.py#L194

